00:43:25.450 --> 00:43:31.070
AUDIENCE: Did you ever
feel-- did you ever

00:43:31.070 --> 00:43:35.490
feel like you were in danger in
some of the places you visited?

00:43:35.490 --> 00:43:36.450
EMILY VOIGT: Yeah.

00:43:36.450 --> 00:43:38.145
I always felt like
I was in danger.

00:43:38.145 --> 00:43:43.720
But whether I was
actually in-- I

00:43:43.720 --> 00:43:45.990
said last night with the
book launch-- somebody

00:43:45.990 --> 00:43:46.990
asked the same question.

00:43:46.990 --> 00:43:49.410
And I said that,
basically, I was always

00:43:49.410 --> 00:43:50.630
worried about something.

00:43:50.630 --> 00:43:53.130
So for example, when I had to
get to the heart of Borneo,

00:43:53.130 --> 00:43:55.610
I was worried about these
three different things.

00:43:55.610 --> 00:43:57.986
People had warned me that
there were Islamic terrorists

00:43:57.986 --> 00:43:59.610
in the jungle and
there was an election

00:43:59.610 --> 00:44:02.870
about to happen in Indonesia
so that they would potentially

00:44:02.870 --> 00:44:04.545
want to kidnap somebody.

00:44:04.545 --> 00:44:06.920
So I couldn't even get a travel
agency to help me at all.

00:44:06.920 --> 00:44:09.590
And I was worried about that.

00:44:09.590 --> 00:44:12.410
I was worried about
the fish mafia

00:44:12.410 --> 00:44:14.640
because I could never tell
if it was real or not.

00:44:14.640 --> 00:44:17.550
So I'd be talking to
people and wanting

00:44:17.550 --> 00:44:19.630
to ask about the fish
mafia, but also wondering

00:44:19.630 --> 00:44:23.160
if they were part of it.

00:44:23.160 --> 00:44:25.600
It sounds very funny,
but at the time,

00:44:25.600 --> 00:44:27.530
I was a little nervous about it.

00:44:27.530 --> 00:44:30.560
And the other thing
was headhunters.

00:44:30.560 --> 00:44:35.340
So the indigenous people
that live on this lake

00:44:35.340 --> 00:44:38.360
were traditionally headhunters.

00:44:38.360 --> 00:44:41.370
So I got warned that there was
still headhunting going on.

00:44:41.370 --> 00:44:43.320
And that I thought was
totally ridiculous.

00:44:43.320 --> 00:44:47.230
I'm like, this is-- it
doesn't happen anymore.

00:44:47.230 --> 00:44:49.110
It's this like horrible
characterization

00:44:49.110 --> 00:44:51.850
of a peaceful tribe.

00:44:51.850 --> 00:44:53.820
I was wrong about that.

00:44:53.820 --> 00:44:55.770
So I was always worried
about something.

00:44:55.770 --> 00:44:57.900
And I was always
worried about the thing

00:44:57.900 --> 00:44:59.460
I shouldn't have been
worried about and not worried

00:44:59.460 --> 00:45:00.501
about what I should have.

00:45:03.500 --> 00:45:04.570
So that was happening.

00:45:04.570 --> 00:45:07.110
But it kept getting worse
and worse in a way, too.

00:45:07.110 --> 00:45:08.860
So by the end of the
book, I was like, OK,

00:45:08.860 --> 00:45:10.818
I'm just going to go to
the Amazon really quick

00:45:10.818 --> 00:45:11.680
and meet Heiko.

00:45:11.680 --> 00:45:13.100
And then he sent
me the itinerary.

00:45:13.100 --> 00:45:19.250
And it was like the hub of
the FARC activity in Colombia.

00:45:19.250 --> 00:45:23.850
And I felt like this fish had
put me through the wringer

00:45:23.850 --> 00:45:24.500
by the end.

00:45:27.302 --> 00:45:28.266
So the answer is yeah.

