is, with the rise of the
Chinese middle class--

00:48:34.250 --> 00:48:38.590
the arowana became popular
first in Taiwan, then Japan,

00:48:38.590 --> 00:48:40.420
and now it's China.

00:48:40.420 --> 00:48:41.510
It's all about China.

00:48:41.510 --> 00:48:45.750
And so that's had big
consequences on the trade.

00:48:45.750 --> 00:48:50.500
And so Aquarama's happening
in the fall in Guangzhou.

00:48:50.500 --> 00:48:54.070
So I may be there
with the Baby Bjorn.

00:48:54.070 --> 00:48:55.555
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:55.555 --> 00:48:56.935
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:48:56.935 --> 00:48:59.340
Is the fish world--
the black market--

00:48:59.340 --> 00:49:01.850
is it a very small world
that everyone knows everyone?

00:49:01.850 --> 00:49:04.100
And they're like why is
this blonde lady poking

00:49:04.100 --> 00:49:05.560
around kind of thing?

00:49:05.560 --> 00:49:07.700
Or is it just big,
and it's random,

00:49:07.700 --> 00:49:10.337
and they didn't know about
you before you met them?

00:49:10.337 --> 00:49:11.920
EMILY VOIGT: No, it
was the first one.

00:49:11.920 --> 00:49:12.699
AUDIENCE: Really?

00:49:12.699 --> 00:49:13.240
Really small?

00:49:13.240 --> 00:49:15.230
EMILY VOIGT: It was
definitely the first one.

00:49:15.230 --> 00:49:18.220
And also, I stuck out
a lot because it's

00:49:18.220 --> 00:49:20.600
a hobby that's pretty much
predominantly Asian men.

00:49:20.600 --> 00:49:23.590
So I would go to these
fish conferences.

00:49:23.590 --> 00:49:25.210
And it was kind of obvious.

00:49:25.210 --> 00:49:27.470
And at first, people were
incredibly welcoming.

00:49:27.470 --> 00:49:29.020
So it is kind of a closed world.

00:49:29.020 --> 00:49:35.236
But the US is also the
largest market for pet fish.

00:49:35.236 --> 00:49:37.520
So the fact that
it's a closed market

00:49:37.520 --> 00:49:40.740
is not great for the industry.

00:49:40.740 --> 00:49:42.956
And so there's an interest
in opening up the US.

00:49:42.956 --> 00:49:45.080
And they've been trying to
communicate with the US.

00:49:45.080 --> 00:49:47.000
And I have to say
that-- American policy--

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:49.280
it's not exactly informed.

00:49:49.280 --> 00:49:51.769
There's not deep knowledge
about the fish that informed

00:49:51.769 --> 00:49:53.060
the fact that it's banned here.

00:49:53.060 --> 00:49:55.600
Whether or not it should be--
that's a different question.

00:49:55.600 --> 00:49:56.910
But they were just
happy to have somebody

00:49:56.910 --> 00:49:58.326
who was paying
attention, finally,

00:49:58.326 --> 00:50:01.574
who might be able to communicate
the real message of the fact

00:50:01.574 --> 00:50:03.240
that these fish are
farmed and so forth.

00:50:03.240 --> 00:50:06.740
And so I found that gave me a
lot of access, which was great.

00:50:06.740 --> 00:50:09.690
But what was funny was
that as the project went on

00:50:09.690 --> 00:50:11.300
for years and years--
like I would run

00:50:11.300 --> 00:50:12.780
into them all over the world.

00:50:12.780 --> 00:50:14.520
So at a fish
convention in Jakarta.

00:50:14.520 --> 00:50:17.890
And then the next fall,
they see me in Guangzhou.

00:50:17.890 --> 00:50:21.190
It became apparent to
them that I was just

00:50:21.190 --> 00:50:23.030
chasing this fish all the time.

00:50:23.030 --> 00:50:25.324
And they would tell
me, what are you doing?

00:50:25.324 --> 00:50:26.740
You haven't written
your book yet?

00:50:26.740 --> 00:50:31.270
I would say, no, no, I'm
studying your obsession.

00:50:31.270 --> 00:50:33.507
And they would look
at me and like--

00:50:33.507 --> 00:50:35.090
you should examine
your own obsession.

00:50:35.090 --> 00:50:36.630
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:38.190 --> 00:50:41.150
They're going back
to their daily jobs.

00:50:41.150 --> 00:50:42.990
The fish is a fun
side thing for them--

00:50:42.990 --> 00:50:48.090
even the most passionate,
whereas I was like,

00:50:48.090 --> 00:50:51.250
I'm going to find this
thing in the wild.

00:50:51.250 --> 00:50:52.450
Yes.

00:50:52.450 --> 00:50:54.540
I definitely was noticed.

00:50:54.540 --> 00:50:55.690
I didn't go under cover.

00:50:59.162 --> 00:51:00.392
Any other questions?

00:51:04.100 --> 00:51:07.276
AUDIENCE: So what makes
a fish worth $100,000

00:51:07.276 --> 00:51:12.630
versus $10,000 versus
$50,000 in the arowana world?

00:51:12.630 --> 00:51:14.590
EMILY VOIGT: So I
know probably more

00:51:14.590 --> 00:51:21.220
than I care to about the details
of what makes a fish valuable.

00:51:21.220 --> 00:51:23.500
It's really rarity and
the perception of rarity.

00:51:23.500 --> 00:51:25.540
So in the case of
the albinos, the idea

00:51:25.540 --> 00:51:27.450
was that they don't
come-- that's what's

00:51:27.450 --> 00:51:29.040
so ridiculous about
the albinos, too.

00:51:29.040 --> 00:51:34.800
Because the normal fish is
valued for its coloration.

00:51:34.800 --> 00:51:37.690
And super red is valued
because it's super red.

00:51:37.690 --> 00:51:40.260
It's right there in the name.

00:51:40.260 --> 00:51:43.380
So if you have a fish that's
born not being red at all,

00:51:43.380 --> 00:51:45.370
it seems like it
would be worth less.

00:51:45.370 --> 00:51:48.250
But it's totally white.

00:51:48.250 --> 00:51:51.794
But it's cool because
it's something

00:51:51.794 --> 00:51:52.960
that people don't see a lot.

00:51:52.960 --> 00:51:56.067
And it has this
perception of rarity.

00:51:56.067 --> 00:51:57.400
And it's really a status symbol.

00:51:57.400 --> 00:51:59.483
So if you can have something
that nobody else has,

00:51:59.483 --> 00:52:01.310
that's the big draw.

00:52:01.310 --> 00:52:04.610
And so that's why the
albino sell for six figures.

00:52:04.610 --> 00:52:09.180
In terms of the other fish,
it's how red they are,

00:52:09.180 --> 00:52:09.970
it's their scales.

00:52:12.850 --> 00:52:16.550
So there's all these things
that can go wrong on the fish.

00:52:16.550 --> 00:52:19.220
Basically, you don't want
the fish to look depressed.

00:52:19.220 --> 00:52:24.140
And sometimes-- they have these
large eyes, kind of like coins.

00:52:24.140 --> 00:52:26.880
When they're in tanks--
I'm not exactly sure why,

00:52:26.880 --> 00:52:29.310
but it has to do
with where they look.

00:52:29.310 --> 00:52:31.280
They're normally in dark water.

00:52:31.280 --> 00:52:33.537
And so I think they're
just looking all over.

00:52:33.537 --> 00:52:35.370
And when they're in a
tank, for some reason,

00:52:35.370 --> 00:52:36.576
they look down a lot.

00:52:36.576 --> 00:52:37.200
They look down.

00:52:37.200 --> 00:52:38.030
Maybe they are depressed.

00:52:38.030 --> 00:52:38.571
I don't know.

00:52:38.571 --> 00:52:41.220
But they get these fatty
deposits up here so

00:52:41.220 --> 00:52:44.707
that-- it's almost like-- I'm
going to do a car metaphor

00:52:44.707 --> 00:52:47.290
and I'm going to totally mess
it up because I don't know cars.

00:52:47.290 --> 00:52:50.560
But when the wheels
are misaligned,

00:52:50.560 --> 00:52:54.000
you have to get them rotated
or something like that.

00:52:54.000 --> 00:52:57.400
So there's a plastic
surgery that can be done.

00:52:57.400 --> 00:52:59.760
There's a whole cottage
industry in fish plastic

00:52:59.760 --> 00:53:01.760
surgery now for the arowana.

00:53:01.760 --> 00:53:04.550
And I've actually witnessed
some of these procedures.

00:53:04.550 --> 00:53:08.296
And there's a lot
of drama because you

00:53:08.296 --> 00:53:09.920
have to take the fish
out of the water.

00:53:09.920 --> 00:53:10.740
You put it under.

00:53:10.740 --> 00:53:12.410
You take it out of the
water and it lays there.

00:53:12.410 --> 00:53:14.410
But you've got to get
back in so it can breathe.

00:53:14.410 --> 00:53:16.270
So these guys have
to move really fast.

00:53:16.270 --> 00:53:18.090
But you remove
the fatty deposit.

00:53:18.090 --> 00:53:19.340
And the fish gets an eye lift.

00:53:19.340 --> 00:53:20.190
And it looks happy.

00:53:20.190 --> 00:53:24.510
The other thing is you don't
want a fish that's PLJ.

00:53:24.510 --> 00:53:26.170
That means Protruding Lower Jaw.

00:53:26.170 --> 00:53:30.190
And it's really
like-- like that.

00:53:30.190 --> 00:53:31.260
Also depressed.

00:53:31.260 --> 00:53:32.780
Maybe these fish are depressed.

00:53:32.780 --> 00:53:35.950
I don't know why they're having
these different features.

00:53:35.950 --> 00:53:37.750
So you can also get a chin tuck.

00:53:37.750 --> 00:53:46.609
So if your fish were to develop
a PLJ, you can get a chin tuck.

00:53:46.609 --> 00:53:47.650
So these are some things.

00:53:47.650 --> 00:53:51.470
So you do have some control
over the value in that regard.

00:53:51.470 --> 00:53:55.196
But really, it's the
stuff you would expect.

00:53:55.196 --> 00:53:57.680
You want a really red fish.

00:53:57.680 --> 00:53:58.989
That's what you're looking for.

00:54:05.321 --> 00:54:08.472
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
some counterfeit fish?

00:54:08.472 --> 00:54:09.550
EMILY VOIGT: Oh, yeah.

00:54:09.550 --> 00:54:10.050
Yeah, I did.

00:54:13.836 --> 00:54:16.820
So the way you
fake an arowana is

00:54:16.820 --> 00:54:22.160
by manipulating the
coloration so that it looks

00:54:22.160 --> 00:54:23.711
like it's a variety it's not.

00:54:23.711 --> 00:54:25.710
So there are these different
pockets of arowana.

00:54:25.710 --> 00:54:28.600
I mentioned that green--
you don't want a green.

00:54:28.600 --> 00:54:34.780
But there's also different
kinds of gold or different kinds

00:54:34.780 --> 00:54:35.280
of red.

00:54:35.280 --> 00:54:37.321
So there's something called
the banjar red, which

00:54:37.321 --> 00:54:39.110
is not as red as the super red.

00:54:39.110 --> 00:54:43.450
But if you keep it in a
certain kind of environment,

00:54:43.450 --> 00:54:44.850
it will start to turn redder.

00:54:44.850 --> 00:54:46.640
And then, it will
sell for more money.

00:54:46.640 --> 00:54:50.020
And then you put it in
a different environment.

00:54:50.020 --> 00:54:53.640
And it just gets back to the
sort of orangy hue that it is.

00:54:53.640 --> 00:54:56.780
So this actually works
most for the gold.

00:54:56.780 --> 00:55:00.360
If you keep a gold fish in
a tank that's totally white,

00:55:00.360 --> 00:55:03.090
it will start to kind of
adapt to it's environment.

00:55:03.090 --> 00:55:05.219
They don't camouflage
themselves,

00:55:05.219 --> 00:55:06.760
but they do manipulate
their coloring

00:55:06.760 --> 00:55:07.960
based on what they see.

00:55:07.960 --> 00:55:09.210
Actually, this is interesting.

00:55:09.210 --> 00:55:12.090
There was a black
arowana I saw once.

00:55:12.090 --> 00:55:15.130
And it turned out that-- it
wasn't true of this fish.

00:55:15.130 --> 00:55:17.660
But generally,
when that happens,

00:55:17.660 --> 00:55:19.480
it's because they're blind.

00:55:19.480 --> 00:55:22.910
So they're mimicking their
perceived environment

00:55:22.910 --> 00:55:23.807
of total darkness.

00:55:26.440 --> 00:55:28.886
That does have some
effect on the coloration.

00:55:28.886 --> 00:55:30.760
The other thing is-- I
should point this out.

00:55:30.760 --> 00:55:32.600
The fish doesn't take
on its coloration

00:55:32.600 --> 00:55:35.752
for three years for the gold
and six for the super red.

00:55:35.752 --> 00:55:37.210
So when they reach
sexual maturity,

00:55:37.210 --> 00:55:40.670
that's when they come
into their full blush.

00:55:40.670 --> 00:55:44.310
And that means that if
you're buying a fish,

00:55:44.310 --> 00:55:46.580
they're usually sold
at about six months--

00:55:46.580 --> 00:55:50.860
you're buying a fish whose
color you have to guess.

00:55:50.860 --> 00:55:52.840
And so I actually went
with a Japanese buyer

00:55:52.840 --> 00:55:55.190
to assess-- this is
professionally what he does.

00:55:55.190 --> 00:55:56.720
He assesses the babies.

00:55:56.720 --> 00:56:02.020
And he tries to guess
what they're going

00:56:02.020 --> 00:56:04.460
to look like when they get big.

00:56:04.460 --> 00:56:06.847
So you could potentially
sell somebody a green fish,

00:56:06.847 --> 00:56:07.680
tell them it's gold.

00:56:07.680 --> 00:56:09.200
And then three
years later, you're

00:56:09.200 --> 00:56:12.240
gone when it doesn't turn gold.

00:56:12.240 --> 00:56:15.287
So that's the kind of
fish fraud and fakes

00:56:15.287 --> 00:56:17.664
that I'm talking about.

